<div class="container">
    <div class="tutorialBody">
        <div id="content-style" class="section-hero">
            <div class="tutorial-container">
                <h1>Ember.js Tutorial</h1>
            <br>
                <h3 class="h3-color">Step By Step</h3>
                <label>Setting up ember.js is very quick and simple, this tutorial will walk you through how to properly set up a ember.js project.</label>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div id="tutorial-steps">
            <div id="step-one" class="section">
                <div class="stepContainer">
                    <div class="information-content"></div>
                    <h2>
                    Step One
                    </h2>
                <label>First, you will want to install node.js onto your device.</label>
                <p>Below is a link to nodejs.org to install node.js for your device</p>
                <p><a href="https://nodejs.org/en/download/"target="_blank" id="link-style" rel="external nofollow noopener noreferrer">This link</a>will take you to the following page:</p>
                <img src="images/node1.png" alt="node1" id="node-style">

                </div>
            

            </div>


            <div id="step-two" class="section">
                <div class="stepContainer">
                    <div class="photo-content"></div>
                    <h2>
                Step Two
                    </h2>
                    <label>Once you have node.js installed correctly: </label>
                <p><strong>a.)</strong> Open up your command prompt and type the following:</p>
                <h3 id="h3-color">npm install -g ember-cli</h3>
                    <br>
                    <label>This will install all the dependencies associated with ember</label>
                    
                    <br>
                    <br>
                    <br>
                    
                    <p><strong>b.)</strong> Next, type in the following into the cmd prompt:</p>
                    <h3 id="h3-color">ember new projectName </h3>
                    <br>
                    <label>("projectName" can be changed to whatever you want your project to be named as.)</label>
                    <br>
                    <img src="images/cmd3.png" alt="cmd3" id ="cmd-pics">
                    <br>
                    <br>
                    <label>Your cmd prompt should look like the above picture now.</label>

                    <br>
                    <br>

                    <p><strong>c.)</strong>Once npm finishes installing the dependencies, your command prompt should display:</p>
                    <img src="images/cmd4.png" alt="cmd4" id="cmd-pic4">

                    <br>
                    <br>

                    <p><strong>d.)</strong> Now simply follow the instructions where it says to "Get started by typing:"</p>
                    <label>Make sure to first type in:<h3 id="h3-color">cd projectName</h3 >then type in:<h3 id="h3-color">npm start</h3></label>
                </div>
            </div>
            

            <div id="step-three" class="section">
                <div class="stepContainer">
                    <div class="information-content"></div>
                    <h2>
                        Step Three
                    </h2>
                    <p><strong>a.)</strong> Direct yourself to wherever the project folder that you created is in.</p>
                    <label>In this example case, the folder name is "projectName".</label>

                    <br>
                    <br>

                    <p><strong>b.)</strong> Once you find the folder, open it in whatever editor you choose. You will see a lot of additional folders and files stored inside your project</p>
                    <label>-This is because what you did in step 2 installed all the necessary folders and files into your project folder to properly run ember.js</label>
                <br>
                <label>-I opened my project folder in visual studio code. Once opened, you should see something like the following:</label>
                    <br>
                    <br>
                    <img src="images/ember1.png" alt="ember1" id="ember1-pic">
                    <br>
                    <br>
                    <label>-Where you will be writing most of your code is located in the "app" folder.</label>
                    <br>
                    <label>-Here, you will see that the package install automatically provided you with folders to organize your code.</label>

                    <br>
                    <br>
                    <img src="images/ember2.png" alt="ember2" id="ember2-pic">
                    <br>
                    <br>
                    <label>-If you look at the "templates" folder, you will see a file named application.hbs.</label>
                    <br>
                    <label>-This application file is where you will begin writing code for the structure of your website.</label>
                    <br>
                    <br>
                <img src="images/ember3.png" alt="ember3" id="ember3-pic">
                </div>
            </div>


                <div id="step-four" class="section">
                    <div class="stepContainer">
                    <div class="information-content"></div>
                    <h2>
                        Step Four
                    </h2>
                    <p>Great, you've gotten your folders and essential files set up,
                        now how do you actually test if your code is working and if your browser looks the way you want it to?
                    </p>
                    <label>-Unlike a regular .html file, you cannot use live server with VScode. Instead, follow along:</label>
                    <br>
                    <br>
                    <br>
                    <p><strong>a.)</strong> Open up your project folder in the file explorer and type in "cmd" in your project folder to open up the command prompt once more:</p>
                    
                    <img src="images/step4-2.png" alt="step4-2" id="step4-1">
                    <br>
                    <p><strong>b.)</strong> Once open, type "ember serve" and press enter like so:</p>
                        <img src="images/step4-3.png" alt="step4-3" id="step4-2">
                    <br>
                        <label>-After a few seconds or possibly minutes (depending on your internet connection), you should see the following:</label>
                        <img src="images/step4-4.png" alt="step4-4" id="step4-4">
                        <br>
                    <label>-If your build was successful, your command prompt should tell you so like above.</label>
                    <br>
                    <label>-If your build was unsuccesful, copy paste the error message into google and hope for the best.</label>
                    <br>
                    <p><strong>c.)</strong> Copy and paste the url after where it says "Build successful", and paste it in whatever browser you are using.</p>
                    <label>-Now this default page for ember should show:</label>
                    <br>
                                <img src="images/welcome.png" alt="welcome" id="welcome-pic">
                                <br>
                                <label>-If you reach the welcome page: </label>
                        <h3 id="h3-color"><strong>Congrats! You have successfully set up your environment to begin writing in ember.js</strong></h3>
                        <br>
                        <br>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div id="step-five">
                    <div class="stepContainer">
                        <div class="information-content"></div>
                        <h2>Step Five</h2>
                        <p> After you have your project up and running there are a few tips, tricks and things to remember!</p>
                        <p>When running on your local machine before publishing, or anytime you will want to make changes to your project before 
                        republishing, you must run the ember server command above. 
                        </p>
                        <label>When programming you will run into issues & have to correct errors.</label>
                        <label>A great tool to use when debugging is the Ember Test Server!</label>
                        <label>-Follow the steps below to create a test server for your new project:</label>

                        <p><strong>a.)</strong> Open a new command prompt and type the following:</p>
                        <h3 id="h3-color">cd "projectName"</h3>
                        <p>-This will get you into the proper directory.</p>
                        <label>To start the test server type:</label>
                        <img src="images/ember-test-server-1.png" alt="test1" id="ember-test-server">

                        <p>When the test server builds and begins running, a new browser page will be opened that shows all the running or failing tests.</p>
                        <p>As you can see, I purposly showed an example with failing tests to show you what messages you will recieve.</p>
                        <h3 id="h3-color">ember t -s</h3>
                        <img src="images/ember-test-server-2.png" alt="test2" id="ember-test-server">
                        <br>
                        <br>
                        <label>-Below is the browser window that will open.</label>
                        <br>
                        <br>
                        <img src="images/ember-test-server-3.png" alt="test3" id="ember-test-server">
                        <br>
                        <br>
                        <label>You can now write code and test it all in real time!</label>
                        <h3 id="h3-color">Happy Coding!</h3>
                        <br>
                        <br>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
